<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="key">
<key pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<keyStep pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,1141,1280]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<keyLead pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
1. Antenna slightly swollen; wings generally broad; forewing costal area usually with interconnected crossveins proximal to pterostigmal area (
<figureCitation box="[727,854,1178,1204]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[233,1352,274,1794]" captionTargetId="figure-11@7.[227,1366,265,1804]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. Baliga kashmirensis sp. nov. Right fore- and hind wing. A. Male (CAUPK00001). B. Female (CAUPK00002). Abbreviations: A = anal vein; C = Costa; CuA = cubitus anterior; CuP = cubitus posterior; MA = media anterior; MP = media posterior; pB = posterior Banksian line; Pt = pterostigma; Sc = subcosta; R = radius.Scale bars = 2.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862208" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862208/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2A–B</figureCitation>
)........................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Navas, 1912" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1912" box="[1157,1399,1178,1205]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Baliga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1157,1237,1178,1205]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Baliga</emphasis>
Navás, 1912
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,1141,1280]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<keyLead pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
– Antenna obviously swollen; wings relatively narrow; forewing costal area without interconnected crossveins proximal to pterostigmal area (
<figureCitation box="[728,798,1253,1280]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[241,1353,301,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-12@15.[227,1353,291,1904]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. Myrmeleon tenuipennis Rambur, 1842. Right fore- and hind wing. A. Male (CAUPK000010). B. Female (CAUPK000011). Scale bars = 2.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862225" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862225/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) .................................. 
